reporting-org.narrative: The federal government of the United States

title.narrative: Banking and Financial Services - Zambia. Banking & Financial Services - Zambia

description.narrative: Support the establishment of a sound private, well-functioning, equitable financial sector that fulfills critical roles in a market economy, most importantly financial intermediation – the efficient generation and allocation of savings to their most productive use.

This award strives to support the establishment of a sound private, well-functioning, equitable financial sector that fulfills critical roles in a market economy. More specifically, this includes Project is closed. The advisors are working with the Central Bank of Zambia on improving capacity to regulate and supervise the Zambian banking sector, with a focus on problem banks. Specifically, the ability of the Bank Supervision Department will be enhanced to ensure the appropriate on-going examination of problem banks; ensure the BoZ’s licensing process follows prudential “fit-and-proper” practices; and, ensure the department has a prudentially sound Early Warning System in place. Problem bank supervision policies and procedures will be developed and implemented that provide internationally acknowledged best practices regarding the drafting, delivering, and tracking of necessary enforcement actions. They are also helping develop a comprehensive Problem Bank Resolution Framework, beginning with the aforementioned Early Warning System, and including every step in the process from special or enhanced supervision through final resolution.. Project is closed..

participating-org.narrative: The federal government of the United States

owner-org.narrative: The federal government of the United States

description.narrative: Despite its status as a lower-middle income country with mineral wealth, Zambia ranks poorly on human development indicators with child malnutrition and its rural poverty levels among the highest in the world. U.S. assistance to Zambia seeks to reduce poverty through the promotion of agriculture-led economic development and food security; combat deforestation and wildlife poaching; expand and improves the quality of health and education opportunities; fight HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis, and malaria; work to decrease maternal and child mortality; strengthen democratic and accountable governance; and build Zambian capacity to promote regional peace, security, and stability.
